<Author>crashbpm
<Content>Good Deal in Theory, But Some MAJOR problems My wife and I were spending two days in Barcelona after a couple of weeks at a villa in Costa Brava and chose The Market based on a mention in Conde Nast Traveler. Our criteria in looking for a hotel: someplace affordable but also central, stylish and comfortable.We discovered that The Market met the first two criteria -- and came to regret not paying more attention to the Trip Advisor Reviews we had read complaining about the noise problems at the hotel. The hotel is in a good area. The entry is located on a mews/alley in an area that is very near all the central sites and shopping. And it looks amazing -- stylish and chic while also being understated. And we couldn't argue with the price -- about 90 Euros a night.But we discovered there was a huge disparity in rooms. We were traveling with a friend who had booked a single and was given a really great room with a balcony and a four-poster bed (ie a room that looks like the one featured on the website). My wife and I were shocked when we opened our room to find it was half the size of our friend's room. Our room was tiny -- almost felt more like a hip single hostel room -- with just enough space for the bed and one suitcase (good thing we only had one suitcase). While our friend had great light through a big window, we had small windows that looked onto the mews and got not light.I am usually the type to complain and try to switch rooms in these sorts of situations, but we had arrived late after a long drive and we just wanted to get to bed. We figured that we only wanted to use our room to sleep.And that's where the real problems began: to say the rooms lack soundproofing is an understatement. We could hear EVERYTHING that was going on throughout our floor. If someone flushed the toilet, we heard the water gushing through the pipes in the wall. The opening of the hall doors echoed through our room. We could hear every word of a conversation in the room next to ours -- and it wasn't because our neighbors where being loud or inconsiderate. And then the construction began at 7 AM on the apartments in higher floors...They obviously skimped on the soundproofing and insulation when constructing this place (it is a converted apartment building). I have stayed in dive motels with better soundproofing.We def. will not be back...and would warn anyone traveling with decent size bags or children to stay away.OH and there is no on-site parking or valet. No one to take your bags to your room. The parking is in a private facility across the street that has an arrangement with the hotel -- although when I tried to park my car there at 1 AM the attendant refused to take my car, saying the lot was full. It was only after begging in broken Spanish that he allowed me to leave it there.On the plus side, the breakfast is nice (but simple) and the restaurant is good for dinner. 
