<Author>Stampy
<Content>If you need more than 3 hours sleep a night - DON'T stay here Overall the decor of the hotel is nice, the area hasn't got a lot going on but is not at all touristy which makes a nice change, and it is only a ten minute walk to a lot of the sights. Oh, and the shower in the room is excellent.That's all I can say that is positive about this hotel. I have stayed in hotels in busy cities, particularly in Asia, and have never experienced the level of noise during the night as I did at the Market Hotel. Whilst the external noise is not the fault of the hotel, the atrocious soundproofing is. The windows were of such poor quality at keeping the noise out that I had to keep checking they had glass in!My wife is normally a deep sleeper, and it takes a lot for her to be disturbed, but she suffered as much as me (and I had the foresight to take earplugs).The only time the noise abated was between around 2.00am and 4.00am. There was a nightclub down the alley which may as well have been in the room. When I went down to reception to enquire what time it was likely to close, they told me 1.00am. As it was already 2.00am I assume it was a time travelling nightclub.The building work started very early, just as you thought you may get an extra hour to make up for the lack of sleep during the night.When I approached reception about the problems they were completey indifferent. They had no alternative rooms and would not assist in locating another hotel. As we were in Barcelona to attend a wedding, we didn't have time to move ourselves.Normally at a wedding you like to have your clothes as crease free as possible. To this end I approached reception to ask to borrow an iron. I was told that it would be brought straight up to my room. 40 minutes later nothing. I rang down several times but no answer, so I went myself. It took me several minutes to locate the person who had promised me the iron, who confirmed he had completely forgotten. He located me an ironing board, but said he couldn't find the iron. No apology, just more indifference. Whilst an ironing board did fulfil 50% of my request, it was 100% useless without the other half. Not a major hiccup, but indicative of the things that just weren't right. Another example was the cheap and good food in the restaurant, which was accompanied by filthy cutlery.We really enjoyed our four nights in Barcelona (despite being creased and tired) and will definately go back. We just won't be staying here, and would advise anyone else to avoid it. 
